WorkItem.Description:
So the [previous issue](https://typescript.codeplex.com/workitem/933) for partial classes was dismissed as impossible out of hand, but I don't think that's the case at all. There are at least 2 ways I can think of to implement them.

1) Make it a compile-time only feature. Just have the compiler combine the code of the two classes and check for conflicts between members. The compiler already is capable of validating subclasses, so this doesn't appear to be that vastly different. Obviously the unified class would only be emitted in one of the output files or a single unified file.

2) Actually generate JavaScript for a partial class that could even be extended at runtime. Consider the following hypothetical TypeScript:

``` TypeScript
//FileA.ts
partial class Dog{		
    constructor(public name: string){}

    bark(): string{return 'woof';}
}

//FileB.ts
partial class Dog{
    eat: string() { return 'num num'; }
}
```

Could generate the following JavaScript:
``` JavaScript
//FileA.js
var Dog = Dog || function (name) { this.name = name; }
var Dog = (function (Dog) {
    Dog.prototype.bark = function () {
        return 'woof';
    };
    return Dog;
})(Dog);

//FileB.ts
var Dog = Dog || function (name) { this.name = name; }
var Dog = (function (Dog) {
    Dog.prototype.eat = function () {
        return 'num num';
    };
    return Dog;
})(Dog);
```
Try it, it works. The major change here from vanilla classes is that the constructor function needs to be generated outside the function that assigns the prototype and passed in as an argument. The compiler would need to be smart enough to duplicate that constructor function in each file that contains the partial class, so you don't have a "which file is executed first" scenario.

Use case:
I'm generating some TypeScript classes from a tool and I'd like to extend them in another file without subclassing them. For application-scale projects, partial classes are a handy tool to have in your toolbelt.

Comments.Message:
But JavaScript is prototypical - classes and inheritance are just conceptual ideas we use at the source-level, there are no classes in JS.

Maybe we need to re-think the partial concept for JavaScript a little bit.

In JavaScript, load order *does* matter, because we don't have such a thing as static class definitions. Classes are actually code that *runs* and constructs the "classes" (prototypes) one method at a time, so this is very different from e.g. C# where class definitions are static.

We also need to consider how somebody would decorate a "class" with new methods in JavaScript - the "class", initially, is always "partial" in JavaScript, in the sense that it's prototype is always open to further modification, and the constructor itself can be overwritten at will.

So first off, I think we're looking at two different types of declarations - a regular class definition, followed by one or more "partial" class definitions that extend the actual class definition:

	class Dog {
		private _name: string;

		constructor(name: string) {
			this._name = name;
		}

		public bark() {
			return this._name + ' says: woof!';
		}
	}

	partial class Dog {
		private _ate: string[];

		constructor(name: string) {
			parent(name: string); // call previous constructor
			this._ate = [];
		}

		public eat(food: string) {
			return this._name + ' eats: ' + food + ' (nom nom)';
			this._ate.push(food);
		}
	}

Note that I introduced a `parent` keyword here, so that when overriding the constructor (or other methods) in a partial class, you can call the `parent` method - this would provide the same degree of flexibility that JavaScript provides, as far as being able to call the original method (or not) at any time, as well as being able to modify it's return value if needed.

The compiled output for regular classes doesn't need to change:

    var Dog = (function () {
        function Dog(name) {
            this._name = name;
        }
        Dog.prototype.bark = function () {
            return this._name + ' says: woof!';
        };
        return Dog;
    })();

The compiled output for partial classes would assume the class has already been defined, and would simply replace the class - for example, the compiled partial class might replace the existing definition of `Dog`, and copy members from the prototype of the existing "class":

    Dog = (function (parent) {
        function Dog(name) {
            parent.call(this, name);
            this._ate = [];
        }
        for (var member in parent.prototype) {
            Dog.prototype[member] = parent.prototype[member];
        }
        Dog.prototype.eat = function (food) {
            return this._name + ' eats: ' + food + ' (nom nom)';
            this._ate.push(food);
        };
        return Dog;
    })(Dog);

I tested this, and it seems to work - I think this is more true to JavaScript semantics? Typically, when you see classes being extended with "plugins" in JavaScript libraries, the extension is a little "invasive" operation on the existing constructor or "class" along the lines of this.

Maybe there's a better/cleaner/faster way to accomplish something similar?

I think, ideally, overwriting `Dog` should actually be avoided, so that copying all the members from the parent prototype could be avoided, but I was unable to find any other way to replace the actual constructor.

Anyhow, I hope maybe this gives a basis for further discussion.

Just as the `var _this = this;` injection is avoided when `this` is not used in a lambda function, you could avoid overwriting the Class and copying the prototype members if a new `constructor` is not declared - therefore only adding to the prototype.

(function (Partial) {
    Partial.prototype.eat = function (food) {
        return this._name + ' eats: ' + food + ' (nom nom)';
        this._ate.push(food);
    };
})(Dog);

Why wouldn't you choose to just extend the interface?
```TS
//FileA.ts
 class Dog{      
    	constructor(public name: string){}
    	bark(): string{return 'woof';}
	}	

//FileB.ts
interface  Dog {
    eat(str:string): string;
}

Dog.prototype.eat= function(str){
    return ("woof woof");
}
```

Abuse of partials could ultimately hurt the advantage TS brings to the table.  I would prefer seeing a new class if introducing new properties but given the reliance on generated code below could be a better way
```TS
//FileB.ts
extend interface Dog {
        eat(food:string): string{return 'woof woof';}
}

```
 I like it better because accessing the prototype in TypeScript just begs to cause issues in the future as the language develops

What I ended up doing is generating a base class and then extending it.

```
//DogBase.ts
// this file is generated.  Any modifications will be overwritten by the next generate.
 class DogBase{      
        constructor(public name: string){}
        bark(): string{return 'woof';}
 }

//Dog.ts
class Dog extends DogBase {
        constructor(name: string){super(name);}
        eat(food:string): string{return 'woof woof';}
}
```

